  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it’s something I’ve felt myself, even as an electrician in New York. My dad, who had a PhD, taught me to respect knowledge, but my own education stopped at primary school. I’ve seen how kids from my neighborhood, especially girls, get nervous when they’re in classrooms where boys are expected to dominate science. It’s not about being smart or not—it’s about the fear that their identity might be labeled wrong. When a girl says, 'I’m not good at math,' it’s not just a lack of confidence; it’s the weight of stereotypes telling her she’s not meant for this field. I’ve always been anxious about things I don’t understand, so I can’t help but think that stereotype threat makes people freeze up before they even try. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with big lectures or programs that don’t connect to real life. For example, when I fix a circuit, I tell my kids to focus on the problem, not the stereotype. I’ve seen how a simple conversation about effort, not ability, can help them feel more in control. We need to create spaces where people feel safe to make mistakes, like when I teach my grandkids to use a multimeter—they don’t have to be perfect to learn. It’s about changing the way we talk, not the way we teach. And if we don’t, the next generation might never see themselves in STEM because they’re too scared to try.",
